    {
      "id": "96cfae0ea0c8e4e5d3364a11b91b52fb59b29f59",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 15:00:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI don't understand this patch. I see kernel stuff but its not used and then it looks like the kernel lz4 work is ported to user land. A lz4 library already exist.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e8196d64d4d675e12bf1556c631fd251ba66864a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 743,
        "name": "Anna Fuchs",
        "email": "anna.fuchs@informatik.uni-hamburg.de",
        "username": "fuchs"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 15:04:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> I don't understand this patch. I see kernel stuff but its not used\n > and then it looks like the kernel lz4 work is ported to user land.\n > A lz4 library already exist.\n\nThis patch is part of a series of patches for compression support in Lustre (see ticket LU-10026).\nWe make use of the kernel modules for compression. In the CentOS-3.10 kernels this module is not available so we decided to backport it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "40b3d74a59310ff90f7e4b7f68daf9968e707f0d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 15:19:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified+1\n\nBuild Successful \n\nhttps://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews-patchless/4422/ : SUCCESS\n\nhttps://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/63185/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "08571b543378fe19604957b845fceeb5c46ee918",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 403,
        "name": "Autotest",
        "email": "autotest@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "autotest",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 15:20:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPatch will not be tested because it is marked forbuildonly",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4e8c048c5d736a101ffa2f039a32e2b4fb554b53",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 16:38:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(12 comments)\n\nSome small stuff, a few questions.\n\nOne further question:\nLZ4 vs LZ4 FAST...  What do we do if only LZ4 is found in the kernel?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "314baaf2f8e9feddb79fc1abe9f2e9dd2b106043",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 17:31:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nThanks Patrick for seeing what he was doing. Since this is a 2.13+ think older kernels then RHEL7 are not supported anymore so we don't need to back port the entire lz4 stack from the kernel. Second I rather use the kernel crypto API to support compression. The reason is that the crypto API can take advantage of hardware that does compress for us. Power8 hardware comes with compression hardware by default. Also lz4 is handled with the crypto api. Lastly lustre already works with crypto api so integrating compress would not be a huge step forward",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d5fc6e4f67310383957ba7e1088456a69575eed3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 17:36:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nRHEL7 *is* 3.10.x, James, so we definitely need this for RHEL7 unless LZ4 has been ported by RH.\n\nNote that the implementation of Lustre connecting to compression is not in this patch, so complaints about using the subsystem or not are out of scope. :)  Adding LZ4 doesn't preclude using the kernel encryption/compression subsystem.  (I can't remember if the implementing patch does, but it could be changed to do so if it does not.)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ff873b7e803af8c62b45c254e52293f04131f57a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 18:10:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe default lz4 has been port for RHEL7. I looked. The \"fast\" version looks to be missing.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d740db7a5267ba397fde999e00e0a1c7284f752f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-05 18:14:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI do want this project to consider the potential to use hardware acceleration which is why I brought up compression in crypto layer.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f70a321eada4cc5a56b5d8319af1e9a8e5b17298",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 743,
        "name": "Anna Fuchs",
        "email": "anna.fuchs@informatik.uni-hamburg.de",
        "username": "fuchs"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-09 17:24:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(6 comments)\n\nPatrick, thank you for reviews!\n> Some small stuff, a few questions.\n> One further question: LZ4 vs LZ4 FAST... What do we do if only LZ4 is found in the kernel?\nCurrently we don't do anything. We would want to add and use the fast-mode then, but it seems to be tricky.\nI'm not sure if you can really split up the module to build only the fast-mode part and keep the old common lz4 compressor.\nIt also doesn't seem to be a good idea to build the complete module and have the common lz4 compressor twice.\nSo for kernel versions >3.10 and <4.11 we only have the old lz4. When using the functionality we currently would need kind of a querie which version is available and how the API looks like.\n\nJames, I understand you doubts, we just try to find the best way to move forward.\n\n> The default lz4 has been port for RHEL7. I looked. The \"fast\" version looks to be missing.\nSince we are a research group at a university, not a part of commercial industry, we and our students use the free CentOS, not RHEL.\nCentOS does not have that speacial patch, so we need that backport. Whether only lz4 lib or together with crypto API, for both we need a backport, since both have been introduced in kernel 3.11.\nI don't know how easy it could be to backport the cryto stuff together with its hardware support.\n\n> I do want this project to consider the potential to use hardware acceleration which is why I brought up compression in crypto layer.\nWe keep that in mind. We have also had a look at Intel's QAT technology, but so far didn't have the capacity to take care of it.\nYou might look at these patches like at the minimal base for proof of concept purpose. Sure, there is a ton of things to be done..",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
